    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Describe the bug\n\nIf your cython source file cimports numpy, the filename table contains a path to a numpy pxd file which is relative to your cython source. Example:  `\"../../../usr/local/python/python-3.11/std/lib64/python3.11/site-packages/numpy/__init__.cython-30.pxd\"`.\n\nThis relative path changes depending on the location of your project which causes ccache misses when using shared ccache. \n\n### Code to reproduce the behaviour:\n\n```shell\n$ cython -V\nCython version 3.3.0a0\n$ cat test.pyx\ncimport numpy\n$ cython test.pyx --cplus\n$ cat test.cpp | grep filename_table -A 5\n/* #### Code section: filename_table ### */\n\nstatic const char* const __pyx_f[] = {\n  \"test.pyx\",\n  \"../../../usr/local/python/python-3.11/std/lib64/python3.11/site-packages/numpy/__init__.cython-30.pxd\",\n  \"venv/lib64/python3.11/site-packages/Cython/Includes/cpython/type.pxd\",\n```\n\n\n### Expected behaviour\n\nThe path to a header file outside the tree should remain absolute. \n\n### OS\n\nLinux\n\n### Python version\n\n3.11\n\n### Cython version\n\n3.3.0a0\n\n### Additional context\n\nMight be related to #6755, I am not sure if this was the intended behavior of that change. ",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "I think the bug is caused by these lines: https://github.com/cython/cython/blob/master/Cython/Compiler/Scanning.py#L195-L199\n```\n        try:\n            self._short_path_description = os.path.relpath(self.path_description)\n        except ValueError:\n            # path not under current directory => use complete file path\n            self._short_path_description = self.path_description\n```\n\nThe comment says \"use complete file path if not under current directory\" but this branch will never be reached because `os.path.relpath` doesn't raise a `ValueError`:\n```\n>>> os.path.relpath(\"/usr/local\")\n'../../usr/local'\n```\nThe correct function to use is `pathlib.Path(...).relative_to()`:\n```\n>>> pathlib.Path(\"/usr/local\").relative_to(\".\")\nTraceback (most recent call last):\n  File \"<stdin>\", line 1, in <module>\n  File \"/opt/python/python-3.11/lib64/python3.11/pathlib.py\", line 730, in relative_to\n    raise ValueError(\"{!r} is not in the subpath of {!r}\"\nValueError: '/usr/local' is not in the subpath of '' OR one path is relative and the other is absolute.\n```\n",
